The Design Process of a 2 directional Flying Device
Preface
The game of Minecraft has lots to offer. It includes many mechanics, each of which has many small
moving parts, all fitting together to create one, magnificent game. One such mechanic which drew my
interest are Piston mechanics. Here, I will detail how I designed a 2-way passenger plane with storage, as
well 2 distinct designs for switching stations and how to fix any mechanical failures that may occur
during flight. This paper assumes that one in-game block has side length of 1 meter.
The Machine
On the 24th of December, 2022, I was building an elevator for a project I had. While designing and
implementing a call feature where the launch button on either floors could be used to call the elevator
from the opposite side, I encountered an error where the platform
part of the elevator would detach from the actual engine itself. I
quickly fixed the issue (Pulse length too short). But as I was fixing
it, a thought came to mind. Minecraft Bedrock pistons do not
have directional limitations like those of Minecraft Java. So in
theory, I could also build this sideways, in the form of a car. And so,
my journey began. I started experimenting with different designs
of my so called sideways elevator.
Design process of the Engine
In order to build a two directional flying machine, one has many hurdles to cross:
The first floor launching
system of the elevator.
1. The flying machine must be able to change direction easily and without requiring the breaking of
blocks or any player action. (Other than starting the machine)
2. The flying machine must be able to change direction indefinitely, with no limitation on how
many times it can change direction.
Normally, a 1-directional flying machine involves 2 parts, one part with a sticky piston to retract the
second part when they get separated, and the other part with a normal piston to push the first part in
the direction of the device. Below is a schematic of the 1 directional flying machine:
This design works when the piston labeled 1 is activated via a signal from the observer marked a.
This will move the topmost 2x2 square one block forward (up in this picture), forming what is described
by the diagram below.
In the game tick (unit of time) in which piston 1 extends, a block update signal is sent to observer b.
This activates piston 2 in the game tick right after, (in which piston 1 also retracts), resulting in the
following figure:
When piston 2 retracts, it pulls the 2x2 with piston 1 and observer a with it, resulting in the
original figure, but moved 1 block forward.
Thus, after just 8 game ticks (0.4 seconds), the flying machine has moved forward 1 block, resulting in a
speed of 2.5 m/s. This design works fine, but it can only move in one direction, and requires the pistons
to switch in order to go the opposite direction. The YouTube video proposes a solution to this problem.
It states 2 basic rules we have to follow to get a design:
1. The design must be symmetric, for full reversibility.
2. Both sides must be able to go in both directions.
Then, it gives us a functioning design.
Instead of a sticky piston and a normal piston, this design only uses sticky pistons. Even then, it still
functions properly, mimicking the behavior of the 1 directional flying machine. There are two parts to
this machine, each capable of running in two modes. For it to function properly, the two segments have
to be operating in opposite modes. From now on, I will be referring to the pistons farther away from the
center the bottom piston, and the pistons closer to the center the top pistons (as in the perspective
of the bottom half of the device).
Mode 1: Pushing Mode.
This mode is active when the observer is in the position farther away from the center of the device, the
mode that the bottom piece the flying machine mentioned above is in. In this mode, when the observer
receives a block update, it powers the bottom piston, which extends and retracts over the course of 2
ticks, using the top piston to push whatever is in front of it forwards by one meter. Since the activated
piston does not push/pull a sticky block, the top section does not come back when the piston retracts
(thus the name Pushing Mode). Long story short, this mode acts like a normal, non-sticky piston.
Mode 2: Retracting Mode.
This mode is active when the observer is in the position closer to the center of the device, the mode that
the top half of the flying machine depicted above is in. In this mode, when the observer receives a block
update, the top piston will get powered directly. Same as Pushing Mode, the piston will extend and
retract over the course of 2 ticks. This time, however, the piston will come in contact with a sticky block,
which will in turn drag the back half forwards with it. It should be noted the section in this mode should
never be activated by hand, only by a block update when the half in Pushing Mode pushes it. This also
means that this section should NEVER be pushing the other section, which can cause mechanical failure.
As per the descriptions above, it is clear to see how similar that design is with the 1-directional design.
However, the real magic of this design is revealed when we move the two observers pictured one meter
up, which can be done using 4 slime blocks in a L shape and a sticky piston attached to it.
If you look closely, you will quickly realized that after this simple operation, we have just functionally
rotated the device 180 degrees. Now, if we apply block update to the observer in the half in Pushing
Mode, the flying machine will go off, back where it came from.
Design of the Plane
In order to turn this engine into a plane, I had to add a passenger bay as well as storage for fully
autonomous flights. Soon, I realized that by taking part of the plane (minus the observer), flipping the
pistons 180 degrees, and attaching two instances of them such that they share the slime blocks, we get
2 more parts that are in the opposite mode of the half they are attached to, perfect for pushing or
pulling a passenger bay along for the ride. I quickly designed a simple passenger bay that is less than the
12 block pushing limit for pistons, as well as an area to hold cargo, and all of a sudden, I had a working
plane in vanilla Minecraft.
Afterword
I had spent a lot of time designing this, and hope that one day people will be able to use it in their own
creations. Also, the design I showed above is still very basic, composing of just two attachments and a
single engine. I hope that in the future, people can create even better versions of my plane. I have yet to
tell many about this design, and I sincerely hope people all around the world can use it as a part of their
creations.
